\begin_layout Title
Summary on A Note Restaurant Pricing and Other Examples of Social Influences
 On Prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Albert Shyn Kwan Tan
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper tries to explain why many successful restaurants, plays, sporting
 events, and other activities do not raise prices even with persistent excess
 demand.
 The approach is that demand of typical consumer is positively related to
 quantities demanded by other consumers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model incorporated that demand of a good by a person depends positively
 on the aggregate demanded of a good:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
D & = & \sum d^{i}(p,D)=F(p,D),F_{p}<0,F_{d}>0\label{eq:1}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{i}(p,D)$
\end_inset

 is the demand of the ith consumer, and D is the market demand.
 Differentiating (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1"

\end_inset

) w.r.t.
 price, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dp}{dD} & = & \frac{1-F_{d}}{F_{p}}\label{eq:2}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

If the social interaction is strong enough - if 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{d}>1$
\end_inset

- an increase in aggregate demand would increase the demand price.
 Note that here, instead of examining the usual how price affect demand,
 we are examining how demand affect price.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{D}>1$
\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $D<D*$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{d}=1$
\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $D=D*$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{d}<1$
\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $D>D*$
\end_inset

, the demand rises as D increases for 
\begin_inset Formula $D<D*$
\end_inset

, it hits a peak 
\begin_inset Formula $D=D*$
\end_inset

, and then it falls as 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 increases beyond 
\begin_inset Formula $D*$
\end_inset

(Figure 1).
 
\end_layout

