\begin_layout Standard
Profits are maximized at price equals 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{max}$
\end_inset

, the peak demand price.
 The positively inclined demand curve in the vicinity of S explains why
 popular restaurants remain popular despite 'high prices'.
 Demand must rationed at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{max}$
\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $D*$
\end_inset

exceeds S.
 Though a firm that charges 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{max}$
\end_inset

has a permanent gap measured by the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $D*$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, it shouldn't raise price further and cut the gap; demand is discontinuous
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{max}$
\end_inset

and falls to zero for trivial increases in price.
\end_layout

