\begin_layout Standard
Demand curve can be negatively first negatively slope, become positively
 slope for some 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, and then become negatively slope again (Figure 2).
 If firm choose price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

, demand may be at 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}^{*}$
\end_inset

or at 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{g}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Though profit is maximized at 
\begin_inset Formula $(D_{g}^{*},p^{*})$
\end_inset

 , firm that must have an inferior equilibrium prefers 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 where marginal revenue zero when 
\begin_inset Formula $p=p_{e}<p^{*}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $D=D_{e}<S.$
\end_inset

 Lessons from figure 2:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are two competing locally profit-maximizing equilibrium: one has excess
 capacity and a low price 
\begin_inset Formula $(S-D_{e},p_{e})$
\end_inset

 and the other has excess demand and a high price 
\begin_inset Formula $(D_{g}^{*}-S,p^{*}).$
\end_inset

The difference between these equilibira correspond to the difference between
 a struggling restaurant or play with excess seats and a highly successful
 one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Suggest that goods with bandwagon properties tend to be advertised heavily
 since demand of one consumer drives the demand of other consumers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The distinctive equilibira 
\begin_inset Formula $D=D^{e}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $D=D_{g}^{*}$
\end_inset

explain why restaurant with similar food and amenities don't do equally
 well
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The price of hardcover edition almost never increases when a book turns
 out to succeed, nor until remaindering does it fall so much that it flops.
 The reason is that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

is more or less the optimal price whether the book flops or not, assuming
 demand is quite inelastic for 
\begin_inset Formula $p<p*$
\end_inset

.
 Publishers set a price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

and hope for success, but they recognize that they may end up with many
 unsold copies that are mainly useful in the remainder market and for paper
 content
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The equilibrium at 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{e,}D_{e})$
\end_inset

 is locally stable, the one at 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{*},D_{g}^{*})$
\end_inset

 is not stable for shocks that reduce demand, and neither equilibrium is
 stable for large changes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is much easier from being successful to being unsuccessful(restaurant)
 than being unsuccessful to being successful.
 This is because
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{e},D_{e})$
\end_inset

 is locally stable in both directions and only a large upward shock to demand
 could shift demand to the profitable equilibrium at 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{*},D_{g}^{*})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The cost from expanding from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{*}^{1}$
\end_inset

may cost firm to bankrupt if initially high demand 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{g}^{*}$
\end_inset

suddenly falls to 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 So, firm may be reluctant to expand capacity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A restaurant could increase leftward stability of a high-price equilibrium
 by lowering price in figure 2 below 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*},$
\end_inset

say 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{p}<p^{*},$
\end_inset

which has a demand at 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{D_{g}}>\bar{D_{g}^{*}}$
\end_inset

; the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bar{p,}\bar{D_{g})}$
\end_inset

 is not only stable for increases in demand but also for some shocks that
 lower demand.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{p}$
\end_inset

 does not avoid multiple equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another reason of why supply does not grow is that aggregate demand depends
 not only on price and aggregate demand but also positively on the gap between
 demand and supply:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
D & = & \sum d^{i}(p,D,\frac{D}{S})=F(P,D,\frac{D}{S}),\frac{\delta F}{\delta S}>0\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Greater supply might not pay because that lowers the gap, and, hence the
 optimal price available to a producer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Miscellaneous & Appendix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Typical consumers may prefer a larger aggregate demand only up to some fraction
 of capacity; beyond that they find the restaurant overcrowded.
 Refer to Question 20 &21 in Encyclopedia which has question on this topic.
 The model we used in class is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{dX_{1}}{dp_{1}} & = & {\displaystyle \sum_{j=1}^{N}\frac{dx_{1}^{j}}{dp_{1}}+\sum_{j=1}^{N}\frac{dx_{1}^{j}}{dX_{1}}\frac{dX_{1}}{dp_{1}}}\\
\frac{dX_{1}}{dp_{1}} & = & \frac{\sum_{j=1}^{N}\frac{dx_{1}^{j}}{dp_{1}}}{1-\sum_{j=1}^{N}\frac{dx_{1}^{j}}{dX_{1}}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the social multiplier effect is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
m & = & \frac{1}{1-\sum_{j=1}^{N}\frac{dx_{1}^{j}}{dX_{1}}}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


